Beijing is — and should be — petrified | The Times

In late April, when President Xi Jinping was touring Xinjiang he described the 
restive, violence-prone western part of the province as “China’s front-line 
on terrorism”. A day later, Xinjiang duly obliged with confirmation: an 
indiscriminate, blood-soaked attack 
on rail passengers at Urumqi station that co-ordinated two suicide bombs 
with a knife rampage by eight assailants.


At one level, China’s propaganda machine is currently engaged in a “we told 
you so” operation. Beijing has argued for many years that the activities of 
some of the Muslim Uighurs in Xinjiang were part of a wider terrorist 
movement that combines separatism with creeping
